patch:
diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp
index d7afe2f426d3..30dc2075b0f0 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp
@@ -2603,6 +2603,43 @@ bool VectorCombine::shrinkType(llvm::Instruction &I) {
   if (KB.countMaxActiveBits() > BW)
     return false;

+  // For shifts, ensure the shift amount is valid for the narrowed type.
+  // Shifting a value of type i1 by any non-zero amount is poison. In general,
+  // after narrowing, the shift amount must be strictly less than the new
+  // element bit-width. Be conservative and only allow constant shift amounts
+  // that satisfy this constraint.
+  if (I.getOpcode() == Instruction::LShr) {
+    if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(OtherOperand)) {
+      // If it's a vector constant, verify each element.
+      if (isa<ConstantVector>(C) || isa<ConstantDataVector>(C)) {
+        unsigned NumElts = cast<VectorType>(C->getType())->getElementCount().getFixedValue();
+        for (unsigned Idx = 0; Idx != NumElts; ++Idx) {
+          Constant *CElt = C->getAggregateElement(Idx);
+          if (!CElt)
+            return false;
+          if (isa<UndefValue>(CElt))
+            continue; // undef shift amount is permitted
+          auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(CElt);
+          if (!CI)
+            return false;
+          if (CI->getValue().uge(BW))
+            return false;
+        }
+      } else if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {
+        if (CI->getValue().uge(BW))
+          return false;
+      } else if (isa<UndefValue>(C)) {
+        // Undef shift amount is permitted.
+      } else {
+        // Unknown constant kind (e.g., ConstantExpr) - be conservative.
+        return false;
+      }
+    } else {
+      // Non-constant shift amount cannot be proven safe for the narrowed type.
+      return false;
+    }
+  }
+
   // Calculate costs of leaving current IR as it is and moving ZExt operation
   // later, along with adding truncates if needed
   TTI::TargetCostKind CostKind = TTI::TCK_RecipThroughput;

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The transformation performed by VectorCombine::shrinkType turns a logical right shift of a zexted value into a shift on the narrower type followed by a zext. In the reproducer, it transforms:
  lshr (zext <2 x i1> %cmp to <2 x i32>), %y
into
  zext (lshr <2 x i1> %cmp, trunc <2 x i32> %y to <2 x i1>) to <2 x i32>
This is incorrect because LLVM's shift semantics require the shift amount to be strictly less than the bit width of the value being shifted. For an i1 type, any non-zero shift amount is invalid and produces poison. In the original IR, shifting i32 by 1 is well-defined and results in 0; after the transform, shifting i1 by 1 yields poison. Alive2 confirms the target becomes more poisonous than the source.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The debug log shows the first transformation is shrinkType, and the resulting IR truncates the shift amount to <2 x i1>. The Alive2 counterexample demonstrates a lane where %y is 1: source produces 0; target produces poison because shifting an i1 by 1 violates the shift constraint. Therefore, shrinkType is applying to an LShr without guarding against the shift amount constraint after bitwidth reduction.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
shrinkType deliberately handles lshr (and bitwise ops) by truncating the non-zext operand to the narrower type and moving zext later. This is valid for bitwise logic ops but not generally safe for shift ops unless we can prove the shift amount is always less than the bit width of the narrowed LHS type. The current code only checks known-bits of the result/users but not the legality of the shift amount for the narrowed type. Consequently, it can produce poison by truncating the shift amount to an i1 when the original shift amount was legal for i32.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
We need to restrict shrinkType for shifts to preserve semantics. A conservative and simple fix is:
- For LShr case, only perform the transform if the shift amount is a constant and for every lane the constant is strictly less than the bit-width of the narrowed element type (SmallBW). Otherwise, bail out.
This avoids complicated per-lane non-constant reasoning and guarantees legality.

Edit (insert guard right after matching and computing SmallBW):
At lines 2586-2602 in VectorCombine::shrinkType, add:

  // If this is a shift, ensure the shift amount is legal for the narrowed type.
  if (I.getOpcode() == Instruction::LShr) {
    // Only proceed if the shift amount is a constant and < SmallBW per lane.
    if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(OtherOperand)) {
      if (auto *CV = dyn_cast<ConstantVector>(C)) {
        for (unsigned Idx = 0, E = CV->getNumOperands(); Idx != E; ++Idx) {
          Constant *CElt = CV->getOperand(Idx);
          if (isa<UndefValue>(CElt))
            continue; // undef shift amount is fine
          auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(CElt);
          if (!CI || CI->getValue().uge(BW))
            return false;
        }
      } else if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {
        if (CI->getValue().uge(BW))
          return false;
      } else if (!isa<UndefValue>(C)) {
        // Non-int constant kinds (e.g., ConstantExpr) we don't handle here.
        return false;
      }
    } else {
      // Non-constant shift amounts cannot be proven < SmallBW; bail out.
      return false;
    }
  }

This guard ensures we only shrink lshr when the truncated shift amount remains valid for the narrower type, preventing the introduction of poison.

5. Conclusion:
The bug stems from shrinking zext across lshr without validating the shift amount post-shrink. Adding a guard to allow the transform only when the shift amount is a constant less than the narrowed bit width eliminates the miscompile and aligns the transformation with LLVM shift semantics. This keeps the optimization for safe cases and prevents generating more poisonous IR than the source.

